{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657484"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20464"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20464"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92877"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13337"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76242"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11579"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31681"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92877"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman gives birth to a baby with characteristic features including hypotonia, upslanting palpebral fissures, a single palmar crease, and a protruding tongue. Karyotype analysis confirms trisomy 21.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the most likely pathophysiological mechanism for this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nondisjunction during paternal meiosis II","Mitotic nondisjunction after fertilisation","Mosaicism arising during early embryogenesis","Nondisjunction during maternal meiosis I","Robertsonian translocation in the father"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely pathophysiological mechanism for trisomy 21 (Down syndrome) in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Enondisjunction during maternal meiosis I\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs when homologous chromosomes fail to separate properly during the first meiotic division, resulting in an egg with two copies of chromosome 21 instead of one. After fertilisation with a normal sperm containing one copy of chromosome 21, the resulting zygote has three copies of chromosome 21.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENondisjunction during paternal meiosis II\u003C/strong\u003E - While paternal nondisjunction can cause trisomy 21, approximately 95% of Down syndrome cases result from maternal nondisjunction, with the majority occurring during meiosis I.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERobertsonian translocation in the father\u003C/strong\u003E - This accounts for only about 4% of Down syndrome cases and involves the attachment of chromosome 21 to another chromosome (usually chromosome 14).\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitotic nondisjunction after fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E - This would result in mosaic Down syndrome, where only some cells have trisomy 21, typically resulting in milder features.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMosaicism arising during early embryogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in approximately 1-2% of Down syndrome cases and results from nondisjunction during early mitotic divisions after a normal fertilisation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of nondisjunction increases significantly with maternal age, particularly after age 35, which is consistent with this case of a 38-year-old mother. The advanced maternal age is associated with deterioration of the meiotic spindle apparatus and cohesion proteins that normally ensure proper chromosome segregation during meiosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nondisjunction during meiosis is the most common cause of aneuploidy in humans.","Maternal nondisjunction in meiosis I accounts for the majority of trisomy 21 (Down syndrome) cases.","The risk of nondisjunction increases with maternal age, particularly after age 35."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 165."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76242"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20464"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76242"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T19:31:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T16:03:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13337"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92877"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7646"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Meiosis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https: